   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="essay">
            <head>
               <bibl>
                  <author type="writer">
                     <name>
                        <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Elizabeth Inchbald</ref>
                     </name>
                  </author>
                  <title type="main" level="a">REMARKS [on <hi rendition="#italics"
                           ><title>Isabella</title></hi>]. <note>"Remarks." <hi rendition="#italics"
                                 ><title><title>Isabella</title>; or, the Fatal Marriage; A Tragedy,
                              In Five Acts; By <ref target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Thomas
                                 Southern</ref>. As Performed at the Theatre Royal, <ref
                                 target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>. Printed
                              Under the Authority of the Managers From the Prompt Book. With Remarks
                              by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                           Inchbald</ref></title></hi>. Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and Orme,
                        Paternoster Row, pp. 3-5. <hi rendition="#italics"><title level="m">The
                              British Theatre; or, A Collection of Plays, Which Are Acted At the
                              Theatres Royal, <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>,
                                 <ref target="people.html#CoventGarden">Covent Garden</ref>, and
                                 <ref target="people.html#Haymarket">Haymarket</ref>. Printed Under
                              the Authority of the Managers from the Prompt Books. With Biographical
                              and Critical Remarks, by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Mrs.
                                 Inchbald.</ref></title></hi> In Twenty-Five Volumes. Vol. VII. <hi
                           rendition="#italics">
                           <title>Isabella</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Oroonoko</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Distressed Mother</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"
                              ><title>Zara</title></hi>. <hi rendition="#italics"><title><ref
                                 target="people.html#GustavIKingofSweden">Gustavus
                              Vasa</ref></title></hi>. London: Printed for Longman, Hurst, Rees, and
                        Orme, Paternoster Row. 1808. The first performance of <ref
                           target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Thomas Southerne</ref>'s <hi
                           rendition="#italics"><title>The Fatal Marriage; or, The Innocent
                              Adultery</title></hi> was staged at the <ref
                           target="people.html#DruryLane">Theatre Royal, Drury Lane</ref> in
                        February of 1694. However, <ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid">David
                           Garrick</ref>'s adaptation, <hi rendition="#italics"><title>Isabella; or,
                              The Fatal Marriage</title></hi>, to which <ref
                           target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> here refers, was first
                        staged at the <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Theatre Royal, Drury
                           Lane</ref>, probably in 1757. Bernadette D. Woodburn, Laura DeWitt, and
                        Mary A. Waters edited this essay for <hi rendition="#italics">The Criticism
                           Archive</hi>. </note></title>
                  <lb rendition="#center"/>______ </bibl>
            </head>
            <p><ref target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Southern</ref>, the author of this tragedy,
               was born in Dublin, in the year of the restoration, and received his education in the
               university there.<note><ref target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Thomas
                     Southerne</ref> was born in 1660, the year <ref
                     target="people.html#CharlesIIKingofEngland">Charles II</ref> was restored to
                  the throne following the English Civil Wars. <ref
                     target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Southerne</ref> attended Trinity College
                  at Dublin from 1676 to 1678.</note> He then came to England, and entered himself
               in the Middle Temple, as student of the law: but he neglected this study for the fame
               of writing plays, and soon after, wholly relinquished it for the adventures of the
                     army.<note><ref target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Southerne</ref> briefly
                  studied law at Middle Temple, London, in 1680 before being drawn away by his
                  interest in theatre.</note> He was patronized by <ref
                  target="people.html#JamesIIKingofEngland">James the Second</ref>, when Duke of
               York, and served under that monarch, as captain, against the <ref
                  target="people.html#MonmouthJamesScott">Duke of Monmouth</ref>.<note><ref
                     target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Southerne</ref> enlisted as an ensign in
                  1685, gradually rising to the rank of captain before his military career ended in
                  1688 with the Glorious Revolution. He served during the <ref
                     target="people.html#MonmouthJamesScott">Monmouth</ref> Rebellion of 1685, an
                  attempt to depose the Catholic <ref target="people.html#JamesIIKingofEngland"
                     >James II</ref> by his protestant half-brother, <ref
                     target="people.html#MonmouthJamesScott">James Scott, 1<hi rendition="#sup"
                        >st</hi> Duke of Monmouth</ref>.</note></p>
            <p><ref target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref> being asked, whose genius, as a
               poet <ref target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Southern</ref> resembled, compared him
               to <ref target="people.html#OtwayThomas">Otway</ref>.<note>From <ref
                     target="people.html#CibberTheophilus">Theophilus Cibber</ref>'s <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Lives of the Poets of Great Britain and
                        Ireland</title></hi> (1753, vol. 5, p. 329).</note> Every reader will own
               the comparison just, for they have both unbounded force in the description of
               poignant grief.</p>
            <p>The present drama, independent of its own worth, will be ever memorable for having
               introduced to the admiration of a London audience,&#8212;<ref
                  target="people.html#SiddonsSarah">Mrs. Siddons</ref>.<note>On October 10<hi
                     rendition="#sup">th</hi>, 1782, <ref target="people.html#SiddonsSarah">Sarah
                     Siddons</ref> played the titular role in <ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid"
                     >David Garrick</ref>'s adaptation of <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>Isabella</title></hi> at <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury
                     Lane</ref>.</note></p>
            <p>Who will allege, that mental powers have no charm in the female sex? <ref
                  target="people.html#SiddonsSarah">Mrs. Siddons</ref> performed on the London
               stage, in the prime of youth and bloom of beauty, yet was totally neglected: She came
               a few years after, with judgment for her aid, and was enthusiastically
                  worshipped.<note>Recruited by <ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid"
                  >Garrick</ref>, <ref target="people.html#SiddonsSarah">Siddons</ref> played
                  Portia, the protagonist of <ref target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam"
                     >Shakespeare</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Merchant of
                        Venice</title></hi>, at <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>
                  in 1775. This performance was not well received, and she was released from her
                  engagement at <ref target="people.html#DruryLane">Drury Lane</ref>. However, her
                  return to play the titular role of <hi rendition="#italics"
                        ><title>Isabella</title></hi> in 1782 was met with phenomenal
                  success.</note></p>
            <p>Woe, bitterest woe, must be gracefully imitated in the just performance of Isabella:
               but of such imitation, and of all those delightful sensations, which arise<fw
                  type="sig"><hi rendition="#smcaps">b 2</hi></fw>
               <pb n="4"/>from beholding fictitious sorrow, the audience of the metropolis had been
               for many years deprived, by the want of skilful tragedians, when she
               appeared,&#8212;she enchanted all the town by her "well painted passion,"<note><ref
                     target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> is quoting <ref
                     target="people.html#ShakespeareWilliam">Shakespeare</ref>'s <title><ref
                        target="people.html#Othello">Othello</ref></title> in Act IV, scene i,
                  spoken by <ref target="people.html#Othello">Othello</ref> in reference to <ref
                     target="people.html#Desdemona">Desdemona's</ref> distress.</note> and
               established in the dramatic world, the long lost prerogative of sighs and tears.</p>
            <p>The characters which surround Isabella, are merely placed there by the author, to
               give effect to all she says and does. Insignificant as those personages are in
               themselves, they produce with her so happy a combination, that a most powerful
               tragedy is the result of their joint services.</p>
            <p>Beyond the deepest pain, felt by an audience for Isabella’s grief, there is a pang
               almost insupportable, which proceeds from her gratitude. The author has in no part of
               the tragedy more effectually wrung the hearts of those, who possess nice sensibility,
               than where this poor widow is overcome by kindness, to render herself additionally
               wretched, rather than be ungrateful.</p>
            <p>"This generosity will ruin me."<note>Found in Act II, scene ii of <ref
                     target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref>'s 1776 adaptation of
                     <title>Isabella</title>, (p. 21)</note> &#8212;"I am contented to be miserable,
               but not this way."<note><ref target="people.html#GarrickDavid">Garrick</ref>'s 1776
                  adaptation of <hi rendition="#italicS"><title>Isabella</title></hi>, Act IV, scene
                  ii, p. 36.</note> These are sentences more pathetic to those, who feel acutely the
               weight of obligations, than any she pronounces.</p>
            <p>Those very auditors are equally vivid in their sensations towards her faults, as her
               virtues; and shrink from the unjustifiable manner with which she treats men who come
               to demand their right; calling them "rav'ning bloodhounds."<note>Act II, scene iii.
               </note> A character, only half as amiable as the author meant her to appear, could
               not conduct herself towards her creditors, but with the most profound respect. Indeed
               was Isabella<pb n="5"/> largely indebted to any one amongst these men, and had not
               the means of payment,&#8212;moral argument, perhaps, could prove, she was bound as
               much in honour to marry <hi rendition="#italics">him</hi> for value received, as to
               marry Villeroy.<note>Villeroy is Isabella's second husband whom she marries after 7
                  years of courting following her husband's supposed death.</note></p>
            <p>This play is censured by some critics for its comic scenes;&#8212;the tragic are much
               superior, they want more of the last, and none of the first. But, more of Isabella,
               exquisite as she is, might cause satiety. The author in his work has given variety,
               and that variegated scene which nature gives.</p>
            <p><ref target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Southern</ref> wrote no less than ten
               plays; of which, only this tragedy, and his <title>Oroonoko</title>, are remembered
               to the author's reputation.</p>
            <p>He lived to the age of eighty-eight,<note><ref target="people.html#SoutherneThomas"
                     >Southerne</ref> died in 1746 at the age of 86.</note> and passed his latter
               days in retired serenity, having acquired, by his industry and strict economy, a
               considerable fortune.<note>This picture of <ref target="people.html#SoutherneThomas"
                     >Southerne</ref>'s retirement reflects that of <ref
                     target="people.html#CibberTheophilus">Theophilus Cibber</ref> in his <hi
                     rendition="#italics"><title>The Lives of the Poets of Great Britain and
                        Ireland</title></hi> (1753, vol. 5, pp. 330-331).</note> He was the first
               who increased the advantage of dramatic authors, by obtaining, in addition to the
               first, a second and third night for their emolument.<note>Benefit nights to
                  supplement the income of a playwright, the actors, or some other beneficiary had
                  become a usual practice by <ref target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref>'s
                  time. They were often negotiated as part of the terms that allowed the play to be
                  staged.</note> He also raised the price of prologues, having given seven guineas
               to <ref target="people.html#DrydenJohn">Dryden</ref>, on his demand of that sum, for
               a prologue, which, till then, had only been rated at five<note><ref
                     target="people.html#JohnsonSamuel">Johnson</ref> says only three. <ref
                     target="people.html#CibberTheophilus">Cibber</ref> says seven was given. It has
                  been thought proper here, to name the most dignified sum [<ref
                     target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref>'s note]. <ref
                     target="people.html#InchbaldMrs">Inchbald</ref> refers to <ref
                     target="people.html#CibberTheophilus">Theophilus Cibber</ref>'s account of the
                  transaction in his <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Lives of the Poets of Great
                        Britain and Ireland</title></hi> (1753, vol. 5, p. 328).</note>. These
               occurrences gave occasion to the following lines of <ref
                  target="people.html#PopeAlexander">Pope</ref>: <quote>
                  <lg type="stanza">
                     <l>&#8212;&#8212;<ref target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Southern</ref>, born
                        to raise</l>
                     <l>The price of prologues and of plays.<note>Slightly altered from <ref
                              target="people.html#PopeAlexander">Alexander Pope</ref>'s poem
                              "<title>To <ref target="people.html#SoutherneThomas">Mr. Thomas
                                 Southern</ref>, On His Birth-day</title>" (1742). The quote in this
                           form first appeared in <ref target="people.html#CibberTheophilus"
                              >Cibber</ref>'s <hi rendition="#italics"><title>The Lives of the Poets
                                 of Great Britain and Ireland</title></hi> (1753, vol. 5, p.
                           328).</note></l>
                  </lg></quote></p>
         </div>
